04528nam a22005415i 9780226818733DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022003329  a9780226818733  a(DE-B1597)638238  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHQ1236.5.M657bB89 2022 4aHQ1236.5.M657bB89 2022 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a305.409517223/eng/202202141 aBuyandelger, Manduhai, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Thousand Steps to Parliament :bConstructing Electable Women in Mongolia /cManduhai Buyandelger. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b34 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on Translation and Transliteration -- tPreface: Hillary Clinton in Mongolia -- tIntroduction: Electable Selves—“ Every Woman for Herself!” -- t1 Legacies: Gender and Feminist Politics under State Socialism -- t2 Electionization: Governing and the New Economies of Democratization -- t3 SurFaces: Campaigns and the Interdependence of Gender and Politics -- t4 Backstage: Inside (Pre)-Campaigning Strategies -- t5 Intellectful: Women against Commercialized Campaigns -- t6 Self-Polishing: Styling the Candidate from Inside and Outside -- tConclusion The Glass Ceiling as a Looking Glass -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA Thousand Steps to Parliament traces how the complicated, contradictory paths to political representation that women in Mongolia must walk mirror those the world over. Mongolia has often been deemed an “island of democracy,” commended for its rapid adoption of free democratic elections in the wake of totalitarian socialism. The democratizing era, however, brought alongside it a phenomenon that Manduhai Buyandelger terms “electionization”—a restructuring of elections from time-grounded events into a continuous neoliberal force that governs everyday life beyond the electoral period. In this way, electoral campaigns have come to substitute for the functions of governing, from social welfare to the private sector, requiring an accumulation of wealth and power beyond the reach of most women candidates. In A Thousand Steps to Parliament, Buyandelger shows how successful women candidates instead use strategies of self-polishing to cultivate charisma and a reputation for being oyunlag, or intellectful. This carefully crafted identity can be called the “electable self”: treating their bodies and minds as pliable and renewable, women candidates draw from the same practices of neoliberalism that have unsustainably commercialized elections. By tracing the complicated, contradictory paths to representation that women in Mongolia must walk, A Thousand Steps to Parliament holds a mirror up to democracies the world over, revealing an urgent need to grapple with the encroaching effects of neoliberalism in our global political systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aNeoliberalismxPolitical aspectszMongolia. 0aPolitical campaignszMongolia. 0aWomen political candidateszMongolia. 0aWomen politicianszMongolia. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzMongolia. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aparliamentary elections, women political candidates, electoral campaigns, Mongolia, politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226818733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226818733/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles